      <hedline>
        <hl1>The New Look of the Senate Race</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>J Edward Waeschle III letter takes issue with characterization of Rick Lazio's record in May 22 editorial (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I take issue with the categorization of Representative Rick Lazio's voting record as being for ''deep cuts in education, Medicaid, Medicare and environmental programs'' (editorial, May 22).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I take issue with the categorization of Representative Rick Lazio's voting record as being for ''deep cuts in education, Medicaid, Medicare and environmental programs'' (editorial, May 22).</p>
        <p>Mr. Lazio and the Republican majority took stands for real increases in those programs and against excessive spending on them. President Clinton initially proposed a status quo spending program that would not achieve a balanced budget until 2005. Through the insistence of the Republican majority, the administration lowered its spending plans and a surplus was achieved in 1998.</p>
        <p>The race for the Senate in New York State should be a race on issues: Mr. Lazio, a proven moderate conservative who stands for home rule, versus Hillary Rodham Clinton, a liberal with no record other than her failed attempt to devise an unwieldy socialized medicine program.</p>
        <p>J. EDWARD WAESCHLE III  Melville, N.Y., March 22, 2000</p>
      </block>
